sentences: As a bandleader, he was noted on the international Jazz scene with his JW European Quartet (originally a quintet), particularly since 2007.
In 2008, he founded the fusion band JW Electrazz.
From 2009, he was based in Berlin, Germany.
Jens Winther was born in Næstved, Denmark, in 1960.
In 1982, he became a solo trumpeter in the DR Big Band and in 1985 he also started to compose for it.
In 1982, he became a solo trumpeter in the DR Big Band and in 1985 he also started to compose for it.
In 1989, Winther left the Big Band and moved to New York City after receiving an invitation to join the two-year Jazz Composer's Workshop under the direction of Bob Brookmeyer.
In 1991, after the end of the workshop, he returned to Denmark.
On 5 May 1994, his first trumpet concerto for symphony orchestra, Concerto for Trumpet and Orchestra, was performed for the first time.
In 1998, he toured with George Gruntz's concert band.
On 29 April 1999, Winther and the Århus Symphony Orchestra performed his second trumpet concerto, The Eagle, for the first time in Århus Musikhus.
In 2007, he experienced an international breakthrough with his JZ European Quintet and went on a worldwide tour which included the United States, Canada, Australia, and China.
In 2008, he formed the fusion band JW Electrazz which had its world premiere on 22 March in Copenhagen Jazzhouse.
In 2009, he moved to Berlin, Germany, and formed the JW Berlin Quintet.
Winther died in Geneva on 24 February 2011.
1982: Sonning's Music Grant
1987 Ben Webster Prize
1992: 3-year scholarship as a composer from the Danish National Art Foundation
1995 Honorary Award from the organisation of Danish Jazz, Beat and Folk Authors
